Yes — all three are involved in handling HTTP requests.
But they operate at different layers and responsibilities.

Even though all of them “handle requests”, they handle different parts of the request lifecycle.

Think of it like a hospital:

Reception (server)
Department routing (servlet)
Doctor (controller)

All deal with the patient — but differently.

1.Server:
Example: Embedded Apache Tomcat

What it does:

Listens on port 8080
Accepts TCP connections
Parses raw HTTP
Creates request & response objects
Manages threads
Passes request to a Servlet

It works at:
👉 Network + HTTP protocol level

It does NOT know:
What /users means
What business logic is

It only knows:
“Someone sent an HTTP request. Let me pass it to a servlet.”


2️.Servlet (DispatcherServlet):
Servlet is part of Java EE specification.

In Spring MVC, the main servlet is:
👉 DispatcherServlet

This is Spring’s front controller.

What it does:

Receives request from Tomcat
Looks at URL
Finds matching controller
Handles validation
Calls controller
Handles response formatting

It works at:
👉 Framework level

It understands:
@RequestMapping
@GetMapping
JSON conversion
Exception handling

3.Controller:
Your controller:

@GetMapping("/users")
public List<User> getUsers() { ... }

It:
Executes business logic
Calls services
Returns data

It works at:
👉 Application logic level

It does NOT care about:

TCP
Threads
Parsing HTTP
Routing rules

Q. Why Can’t One Component Do Everything?

Because of Separation of Concerns.

If controller handled:

Networking
Threading
HTTP parsing
Routing
Business logic

It would be messy and unmaintainable.